Reference for Plan 9 (9front) concepts and idioms vs. UNIX: name spaces, 9P, bind/mount, /proc /srv /net /env, notes vs signals, file permissions, the shell (rc), file servers, distributed model.

# Plan 9 / 9front — Key Differences from UNIX

This skill covers the concepts and idioms that differ most sharply between
Plan 9 (specifically 9front) and POSIX/Linux UNIX, to aid in writing correct
Plan 9 code and scripts.

---

## Philosophy: Everything is a File

Plan 9 takes "everything is a file" further than UNIX.  Network connections,
process state, environment variables, hardware devices, authentication
agents, and UI windows are all accessed by opening, reading, and writing
files.  There is no `ioctl`; configuration and control happen via writes to
control files.

---

## Name Spaces

Each process group has its own private **name space** — a mapping from file
names to objects (files, devices, remote file trees).  Unlike UNIX where all
processes share the same global filesystem root, Plan 9 processes can have
completely different views of the filesystem.

**bind(1):** Binds one part of the namespace over another.

    bind new old          # make old an alias for new
    bind -a new old       # append new to the union at old (search old first)
    bind -b new old       # prepend new to the union at old (search new first)
    bind -c new old       # same as default but allow file creation here

**mount(1):** Mounts a 9P file server service onto the namespace.

    mount /srv/service /mnt/point   # mount a service from /srv
    mount -n /srv/service /mnt/point  # skip authentication

**Union directories:** Multiple directories can be bound to the same path.
Lookup searches them in list order.  Creation goes into the first
`-c`-flagged member.  This replaces the UNIX `PATH`-style search; instead of
having a search path, you bind all your bin directories together under `/bin`.

**rfork(2) and namespace isolation:** `rfork(RFNAMEG)` gives a child process a
copy of the parent's namespace; `rfork(RFCNAMEG)` gives it a blank namespace.
`rfork(RFNOMNT)` disallows mounts into that namespace.  In rc(1): `rfork n`
(copy), `rfork N` (clean).

**UNIX equivalent:** Linux's `mount --bind`, `chroot`, and namespaces
(`CLONE_NEWNS`) are rough analogues, but in Plan 9 every program can use this
routinely via normal system calls.

