## The 9P Protocol

**9P** is the network protocol that glues Plan 9 together.  Every file server
— including kernel devices — speaks 9P.  File operations (`open`, `read`,
`write`, `stat`) are translated into 9P messages (`Topen`/`Ropen`, etc.).

Because all servers speak the same protocol, a user program can implement
a file server that is indistinguishable from a kernel device or a remote
file server.  Tools like `webfs(4)`, `acme(1)`, `plumber(4)`, and `factotum(4)`
are user-space programs that serve file trees over 9P.

**Connection:** A 9P connection is a bidirectional byte stream (pipe,
network connection, etc.).  The server is posted in `/srv`; clients mount it.

**UNIX equivalent:** There is no direct equivalent.  FUSE is a rough analogy.

---

## /srv — Service Registry

`/srv` (bound to `#s`) is a flat directory where processes post open file
descriptors to make them available to others.  Any process can create a file
in `/srv` and write a file descriptor number into it; any other process can
then open that file to get its own reference to the same open file (typically
the 9P connection end of a pipe to a file server).

    # Start a file server and post it
    ramfs -s myfs    # posts /srv/myfs
    mount /srv/myfs /mnt/ram

    # Create a pipe-based service manually
    {ramfs; ...} | mount -c /fd/0 /mnt/x &

**UNIX equivalent:** Roughly analogous to Unix domain sockets or systemd
socket activation, but simpler and integrated with the filesystem.

---

## /proc — Process Filesystem

`/proc` (bound to `#p`) is a directory with numbered subdirectories, one per
running process.  Each contains:

    /proc/n/args        command name and arguments
    /proc/n/ctl         write control commands: kill, hang, stop, start, ...
    /proc/n/fd          list of open file descriptors
    /proc/n/mem         process memory image
    /proc/n/note        write a note (signal-like) to the process
    /proc/n/notepg      write a note to the process group
    /proc/n/ns          namespace listing
    /proc/n/status      process status line
    /proc/n/wait        wait message when child exits

**Sending signals:** There is no `kill` syscall.  To kill a process write
`kill` to `/proc/n/ctl`.  `kill(1)` is an rc script that prints the write
commands; you pipe its output to rc:

    kill processname | rc
    slay processname | rc    # unconditional kill (no grace period)

**UNIX equivalent:** Similar to Linux `/proc`, but older and the model Linux
was partly inspired by.  Key differences: no `/proc/n/maps` style memory
maps; memory access is via `/proc/n/mem`; control is via text writes to
`/proc/n/ctl` rather than signals.

