## /env — Environment Variables

Environment variables are files in `/env` (bound to `#e`).  The name of the
file is the variable name; the content is the value.  Multi-value rc(1) list
variables use NUL bytes (`\000`) as element separators.

    cat /env/user          # print $user
    echo -n glenda > /env/user   # set $user (in this process's env)

`rfork(RFENVG)` copies the environment to a new group (changes isolated).
`rfork(RFCENVG)` starts with a clean empty environment.

In rc(1): `rfork e` is a common idiom at the top of scripts to prevent
variable pollution of the caller's environment.

**UNIX equivalent:** The environment is similar, but in UNIX it is a block
of strings passed at `execve`.  In Plan 9 it is a kernel-managed file
device, making it live and accessible from any process in the group.

