## /net — Network as Files

Network protocols are accessed through the `/net` directory (bound to `#Ispec`).
Each protocol (tcp, udp, etc.) has:

    /net/tcp/clone      open to allocate a new connection n
    /net/tcp/n/ctl      write control: connect, announce, bind, ...
    /net/tcp/n/data     read/write actual data
    /net/tcp/n/local    local address
    /net/tcp/n/remote   remote address
    /net/tcp/n/status   connection status
    /net/tcp/n/listen   accept incoming connections

**Network address syntax:** `network!host!service`, e.g. `tcp!example.com!80`.
The special network name `net` means "any network in common with the host."

**dial(2):** The standard library `dial()` function wraps the `/net` interface:

    fd = dial("tcp!example.com!80", nil, dir, &cfd);

**UNIX equivalent:** BSD sockets are replaced by the file-based `/net`
interface.  There is no `socket()`, `connect()`, `bind()`, `listen()`,
`accept()` syscall API; all of that is accomplished via file operations on
`/net`.

