## Standard I/O and /fd

File descriptors are visible as files in `/fd` (bound to `#d`):

    /fd/0    stdin
    /fd/1    stdout
    /fd/2    stderr
    /fd/n    file descriptor n

Opening `/fd/n` gives you another reference to that file descriptor (like
`dup`).  This allows rc scripts to pass file descriptors to programs:

    prog /fd/3   # pass fd 3 as a file path argument

Redirections like `<>/dev/null` open a single file for both reading and
writing onto a single fd.

---

## /dev Devices

`/dev` (bound to `#c`) contains console and clock devices:

    /dev/cons         console (terminal I/O)
    /dev/consctl      raw/cooked console mode control
    /dev/null         bit bucket (like UNIX /dev/null)
    /dev/zero         source of zero bytes
    /dev/random       random bytes
    /dev/time         time of day (nanoseconds since epoch)
    /dev/pid          this process's pid
    /dev/ppid         parent pid
    /dev/user         current user name
    /dev/sysname      system name (hostname)

Note: there is no `/dev/stdin`, `/dev/stdout`, `/dev/stderr`; use `/fd/0`,
`/fd/1`, `/fd/2` instead.

---

## Kernel "Devices" (#letter notation)

Kernel services are named `#X` where `X` is a letter.  They are bound into
the name space, not accessed directly.  Common ones:

    #c   cons device → /dev
    #d   dup device → /fd
    #e   env device → /env
    #p   proc device → /proc
    #s   srv device → /srv
    #I   IP device → /net (spec is an integer, e.g. #I0)
    #P   pipe device (used internally)
    #|   pipe device (unnamed pipes)

