## Plumber

The **plumber(4)** is a message-routing daemon.  It receives "plumb messages"
(with fields: source, destination, working directory, type, attribute list,
data) and routes them to the appropriate handler based on rules in
`$home/lib/plumbing`.

- Right-clicking (button-3) in acme sends a plumb message.
- The plumber can open files in editors, launch browsers, etc.
- Programs write to `/mnt/plumb/send` to dispatch messages.
- Programs read from `/mnt/plumb/portname` to receive messages.

**UNIX equivalent:** Roughly analogous to `xdg-open` or D-Bus activation,
but programmable via text rules.

---

## Window System: rio

**rio(1)** is the Plan 9 window system.  It is minimalist:

- Windows are resized/moved by right-click dragging.
- No title bars with close buttons; all commands via the menu.
- Each window has an associated `/dev/cons` file.
- Text is selected with button-1; middle-click (button-2) executes a command;
  right-click (button-3) searches/navigates.

**acme(1)** is the integrated text editor and shell environment (see
`acme-vfs` and `acme` skills).

---

## Authentication: factotum

**factotum(4)** is the authentication agent.  It holds secrets and performs
authentication on behalf of processes.  It is a file server mounted at
`/mnt/factotum`.

- Replaces PAM, `~/.ssh/authorized_keys`, Kerberos tickets with a single agent.
- Speaks various protocols: password, p9sk1 (Plan 9 native auth), secstore,
  etc.
- UNIX equivalent: roughly `ssh-agent` + PAM + Kerberos KDC client, combined.

